# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gluhareff-emg-300
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/1994-in-aviation] This is a list of aviation-related events from 1994.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/1994-in-aviation] The deadliest crash of this year was China Airlines Flight 140, an Airbus A300 which crashed on landing in Nagoya, Japan on 26 April, killing 264 of the 271 people on board.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/1994-in-aviation] This accident marked the deadliest single-aircraft crash in the 1990s.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Petersburg, Russia in 1916, was the oldest of two children, born to Michael E.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff was an aircraft engineer who was a former Chief engineer at the Sikorsky Aircraft division of the United Aircraft Corporation, who graduated from the Russian Imperial Military Engineering College (now known as the Saint Petersburg Military Engineering-Technical University).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff graduated from the Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in 1944 with a Bachelor of Sciences in Aeronautical Engineering.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Immediately after his graduation, Gluhareff went to work at Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation in Bridgeport, Connecticut; where he worked under Igor A.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff began his career at the Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation in 1944, one of the initial projects he worked on included the VS-300 and the R-4 helicopters.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff began working on the Pulse Jet Engine in 1947 for Sikorsky.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] In 1950, Gluhareff moved to California in order to work with the company, American Helicopter.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] One of the helicopters he worked on during the early 1950s was the XA-5 "Top Sergeant", a valved pulse-jet powered helicopter.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] In 1953, after working on several other projects, Gluhareff founded the Gluhareff Helicopters Corporation.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Navy in order to develop Rotary Drones in 1960.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] In 1964, Gluhareff joined the Douglas Aircraft Company, where he worked as a Design Engineer Scientist in the development of the S-4 stage of the Saturn Rocket which was part of the Apollo program.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff continued to work with the company, as it became the McDonnell Douglas company, where he eventually became a specialist in rocket stabilization system designing used for ejection seats and capsules.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff returned to EMG Engineering, his own company in 1972, where he continued working until his death, one of the last projects he worked on was the EMG-300, also known as the "Flying Motorcycle", which was designed in the early 1990s.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/eugene-michael-gluhareff] Gluhareff died due to illness whilst he was working on the production and marketing stage of the EMG-300 helicopter in 1994.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-emg-300] The **Gluhareff EMG-300** is a single-seat helicopter with a rotor powered by tip jet engines.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-emg-300] It was designed and built by Eugene Michael Gluhareff in the 1990s.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-emg-300] Although some test flights took place, Gluhareff died in 1994 before development was completed.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-emg-300] The helicopter has a two-blade rotor; each blade has a Gluhareff Pressure Jet engine mounted on its tip.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-emg-300] Only one was built; it is now in the collection of the Pima Air & Space Museum in Tucson, Arizona.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] The **Gluhareff Pressure Jet** (or **tip jet**) is a type of jet engine that, like a valveless pulse jet, has no moving parts.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] It was invented by Eugene Michael Gluhareff, a Russian-American engineer who envisioned it as a power plant for personal helicopters and compact aircraft such as microlights.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] Having no moving parts, the engine works by having a coiled pipe in the combustion chamber that superheats the fuel (propane) before being injected into the air-fuel inlet.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] In the combustion chamber, the fuel/air mixture ignites and burns, creating thrust as it leaves through the exhaust pipe.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] Induction and compression of the fuel/air mixture is done both by the pressure of propane as it is injected, along with the sound waves created by combustion acting on the intake stacks.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] The engine has three intake stages, which are sized according to the sound created by the combustion process when running.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] This has exactly the same effect as the turbine and compressor in a turbojet, creating a vacuum that sucks in air.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] The intakes, along with the exhaust, are sonically tuned so that the locations of the pressure antinodes of the Mach disks in the propane stream match the locations of the intake apertures.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] Thus atmospheric pressure augments air intake as much as possible.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] Early prototypes produced very small amounts of thrust, before Gluharev developed it from early experiments on producing thrust from using the pressurized fuel's kinetic energy to suck in the air and compress it prior to combustion.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] A 1949 reference to a very similar concept exists.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/gluhareff-pressure-jet] Although described as a ram jet, this version heats the fuel within a closed space to create the pressure for injection and compression of the entrained air in a similar manner to the Gluhareff design and is in all fundamental respects a pressure jet of the same type.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] The **Pima Air & Space Museum** is an aerospace museum in Tucson, Arizona, US.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] It features a display of nearly 400 aircraft spread out over 80 acres (32 ha) on a campus occupying 127 acres (51 ha).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] It has also been the home to the Arizona Aviation Hall of Fame since 1991.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] A large number of the museum's aircraft are displayed outside with the remainder located in one of the museum's six display hangars.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] In addition to the display hangars, the museum has a restoration hangar.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] Opened to the public in May 1976 with 48 aircraft then on display, the museum's main hangar houses an SR-71A Blackbird, an A-10 Warthog, a United States Air Force *Through the Years* exhibit, and a mock-up of a control tower.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] The museum is adjacent to Davis-Monthan Air Force Base.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] The 309th Aerospace Maintenance and Regeneration Group (AMARG), affiliated with the base, also known as the "Graveyard of Planes" or "The Boneyard", is the largest aircraft storage and preservation facility in the world.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] The museum opened to the public on May 8, 1976.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] In early 1982 the first hangar on the site was completed.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] A second was built in 1987, a third in 1992, and a fourth in 1994.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] After running into difficulty in the late 1990s, the museum recovered and continued expanding.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] In 1984, construction began on another structure within the grounds of the Pima Air and Space Museum: the 390th Memorial Museum, previously located across town at the Davis-Monthan Air Force Base.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] Moller Library, and later expanded to include a hangar completed in 1987 to protect and display a B-17G on loan from the U.S.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] While the 390th Memorial Museum and the Pima Air & Space Museum are separate entities, they are physically and conceptually associated through their spatial proximity.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] In 2012, the museum collaborated with artists, in *The Boneyard Project*, to place some abandoned aircraft on display as canvases for art.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] During 2015, Boeing donated to the museum a flight test 787 aircraft which is the second built.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] It is exhibited in the colors of the 787 customer, ANA.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] In November 2016, Orbis International donated their first McDonnell-Douglas DC-10 Flying Eye Hospital to the museum, after receiving a second DC-10 from FedEx.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] The DC-10, which was the oldest flying example of its type and at the time of its donation, while being the oldest surviving example and the second overall built, was restored for display at Davis–Monthan Air Force Base.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] The museum acquired 77 acres (31 ha) in January 2021 for the construction of the Tucson Military Vehicle Museum.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] The new museum will house a large number of mostly land vehicles, including 50 donated by the Imperial War Museum.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] A disassembled Martin Mars arrived at the museum in May 2025, having landed at Lake Pleasant three months earlier.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] † B-17G serial number 44-85828 is on display at the 390th Memorial Museum, co-located on the grounds of the Pima Air & Space Museum.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/pima-air-space-museum] In addition to other ephemera, the museum contains the Shuttle Mission Simulator's GNS (Guidance and Navigation Simulator) trainer, and a full-size mockup of the Solid Rocket Booster.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] A **tip jet** is a jet nozzle at the tip of some helicopter rotor blades, used to spin the rotor, much like a Catherine wheel firework.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Tip jets replace the normal shaft drive and have the advantage of placing no torque on the airframe, thus not requiring the presence of a tail rotor.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Some simple monocopters are composed of nothing but a single blade with a tip rocket.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Tip jets can use compressed air, provided by a separate engine, to create jet thrust.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Other designs includes ramjets or even a complete turbojet engine.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Some, known as *rocket-on-rotor* systems, involve placing rockets on the tips of the rotor blades that are fueled from a tank.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] If the helicopter's engine fails, the tip jets on the rotor increase the moment of inertia, hence permitting it to store energy, which makes performing a successful autorotation landing somewhat easier.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] However, the tip jet also typically generates significant extra air drag, which demands a higher sink rate and means that a very sudden transition to the landing flare must occur for survival, with little room for error.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] During the 1900s, Austrian Ludwig Wittgenstein investigated the use of tip jets to drive an aircraft propeller while studying aeronautical engineering at Manchester University, in the United Kingdom.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Wittgenstein's concept required air and gas to be forced along the propeller arms to combustion chambers on the end of each blade, at which point these gases would undergo compression via the centrifugal force exerted by the revolving arms, and thereby generating sufficient heat to achieve ignition.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] During 1911, Wittgenstein was able to secure a patent related to his tip jet work.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Despite the relatively early origins of the concept, achieving the next step of practical application proved to be highly difficult, largely due to propeller designs of the era being relatively primitive and incompatible with the design changes required to implement Wittgenstein's tip jets.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] It would be many years before a blade design that could support the innovation would be developed.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Progress on the jet-powered propeller was further frustrated by Wittgenstein's lack of practical experience with machinery.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] He ultimately lost interest in aviation and discontinued his engineering work.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Wittgenstein would become better known for his later work as a philosopher.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] During the 1920s, the Italian aeronautical engineer Vittorio Isacco designed and constructed several unorthodox rotorcraft which became known as the Helicogyre.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] During 1929, Helicogyre *K1171* was manufactured by British aircraft manufacturer S.E.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Saunders Limited, and was delivered to the Royal Aircraft Establishment (RAE) at Farnborough by road, where it underwent limited testing before the programme was terminated.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Although the Helicogyre did not use tipjets, being instead powered by piston engines positioned at the ends of the rotary wing, Isacco foresaw that these might be replaceable by jets.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Another pioneer in the field of tip jets was the Russian-American engineer Eugene Michael Gluhareff, the inventor of the Gluhareff Pressure Jet.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] During the Second World War, German engineer Friedrich von Doblhoff suggested powering a helicopter with ramjets located on the rotor tips.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] In addition to the WNF 342's experimental use by Germany, two prototypes were obtained by the United States as the conflict came to a close.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Subsequently, Doblhoff joined the American aircraft manufacturer McDonnell Aircraft, which developed and flew the McDonnell XV-1, an experimental compound gyroplane, during the early 1950s.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] The XV-1 was cancelled due to its unfavourable complexity and rapid advances made by conventional helicopters.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] The engineer August Stepan has been credited with producing the tip jet engines used by the British aircraft manufacturing interest Fairey Aviation.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Following the Second World War, Fairey Aviation was keen to explore rotary-wing aircraft, developing the Fairey FB-1 Gyrodyne in accordance with Specification E.16/47.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] The second FB-1 was modified to investigate a tip-jet driven rotor coupled with a pair of propellers mounted on stub wings; it was later renamed the Jet Gyrodyne.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Another rotorcraft developed by the firm, the Fairey Ultra-light Helicopter was a compact side-by-side two-seater vehicle that used tip jets powered by a single Turbomeca Palouste turbojet engine.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] The type led a contract from the Ministry of Supply for four flight test-capable aircraft; the Ultra-light's capabilities were subsequently demonstrated at numerous military exercises, airshows, and even at sea.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] However, the British Army had become more focused on the rival Saunders-Roe Skeeter, allegedly due to interest in the latter from the German government.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Drawn to a specification produced by the airline British European Airways (BEA) for a passenger-carrying rotorcraft, referred to the *BEA Bus*, Fairey set about developing the Fairey Rotodyne.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] On 6 November 1957, the Rotodyne prototype performed its maiden flight, piloted by chief helicopter test pilot Squadron Leader W.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Ron Gellatly and assistant chief helicopter test pilot Lieutenant Commander John G.P.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] On 10 April 1958, the Rotodyne made its first successful transition from vertical to horizontal and then back into vertical flight.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] On 5 January 1959, the Rotodyne set a world speed record in the convertiplane category, at 190.9 mph (307.2 km/h), over a 60-mile (100 km) closed circuit.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Both BEA and the RAF had publicly announced their interest in the Rotodyne, the latter placing an initial order for the type.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Reportedly, the larger Rotodyne Z design could be developed to accommodate up to 75 passengers and, when equipped with Rolls-Royce Tyne engines, would have a projected cruising speed of 200 knots (370 km/h).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] It would be able to carry nearly 8 tons (7 tonnes) of freight; cargoes could have included several British Army vehicles and the intact fuselage of some fighter aircraft within its fuselage.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Despite much of the development work being completed, the British government declared it would issue no further support for the Rotodyne due to economic reasons.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Accordingly, on 26 February 1962, official funding for the Rotodyne was terminated.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] The French aircraft manufacturer Sud-Ouest would be the first company to achieve quantity production of a rotorcraft harnessing tip-jet propulsion.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Having initially developed the tip jet-equipped Sud-Ouest Ariel for purely experimental purposes, the firm had sufficient confidence to proceed with a production-standard rotorcraft, the Sud-Ouest Djinn.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] A single seat prototype, designated *S.O.1220*, was constructed to function as an aerial test bed for the rotorcraft's propulsion concept.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] The French Army encouraged the construction of a large pre-production batch of 22 helicopters for evaluation purposes.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] The first of these flew on 23 September 1954.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Three pre-production rotorcraft were acquired by the United States Army, designating it *YHO-1*, for their own trials; according to aviation author Stanley S.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] McGowen, the US Army held little interest in the type.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] According to author Wayne Mutza, the US Army had found the YHO-1 to be an excellent weapons platform, but were compelled to abandon its interest by political opposition to the procurement of a foreign designed rotorcraft.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] In addition to the French military, a further ten countries placed orders for the type; such as a batch of six rotorcraft which were procured by the German Army.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Production of the Djinn came to an end during the mid-1960s, by which point a total of 178 Djinns had been constructed; the type had effectively been replaced by the more conventional and highly successful Aérospatiale Alouette II.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Some Djinns were sold on to civil operators; in this capacity, they were often equipped for agricultural purposes, fitted with chemical tanks and spray bars.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] During the late 1950s, an improved version of the Djinn, tentatively designated as the *Djinn III* or *Super Djinn*, was being studied by Sud Aviation.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] As envisioned, the projected Super Djinn would have adopted the newer Turbomeca Palouste IV engine alongside other changes for greater power and endurance than the original production model.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Hot tip jets in this context are a form of simple pressure fed rocket engine as both fuel and oxidizer are being supplied, mixed, and ignited.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tip-jet] Typically the oxidizer used here is air that has been compressed elsewhere in the aircraft and ducted through the rotor to the tip thruster along with fuel.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Major incorporated suburbs of Tucson include Oro Valley and Marana northwest of the city, Sahuarita south of the city, and South Tucson in an enclave south of downtown.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Communities in the vicinity of Tucson (some within or overlapping the city limits) include Casas Adobes, Catalina Foothills, Flowing Wells, Midvale Park, Tanque Verde, Tortolita, and Vail.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Towns outside the Tucson metropolitan area include Three Points, Benson to the southeast, Catalina and Oracle to the north, and Green Valley to the south.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson was founded as a military fort by the Spanish when Hugo O'Conor authorized the construction of Presidio San Agustín del Tucsón in 1775.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] It was included in the state of Sonora after Mexico gained independence from the Spanish Empire in 1821.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The United States acquired a 29,670-square-mile (76,800 km2) region of present-day southern Arizona and southwestern New Mexico from Mexico under the Gadsden Purchase in 1853.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson served as the capital of the Arizona Territory from 1867 to 1877.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson was Arizona's largest city by population during the territorial period and early statehood, until it was surpassed by Phoenix by 1920.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Nevertheless, its population growth remained strong during the late 20th century.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson was the first American city to be designated a "City of Gastronomy" by UNESCO in 2015.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Spanish name of the city, *Tucsón* (Spanish pronunciation: [tuɣˈson]), is derived from the O'odham *Cuk Ṣon* (O'odham pronunciation: [tʃʊk ʂɔːn]).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] *Cuk* is a stative verb meaning "(be) black, (be) dark".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] *Ṣon* is (in this usage) a noun referring to the base or foundation of something.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The name is commonly translated into English as "the base [of the hill] is black", a reference to a basalt-covered hill now known as Sentinel Peak.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson is sometimes referred to as the Old Pueblo and Optics Valley, the latter referring to its optical science and telescopes known worldwide.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Tucson area was probably first visited by Paleo-Indians, who were known to have been in southern Arizona about 12,000 years ago.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Recent archaeological excavations near the Santa Cruz River found a village site dating from 2100 BC.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The floodplain of the Santa Cruz River was extensively farmed during the Early Agricultural Period, c.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] These people hunted, gathered wild plants and nuts, and ate corn, beans, and other crops grown using irrigation canals they constructed.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Early Ceramic period occupation of Tucson had the first extensive use of pottery vessels for cooking and storage.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The groups designated as the Hohokam lived in the area from AD 600 to 1450 and are known for their vast irrigation canal systems and their red-on-brown pottery.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Italian Jesuit missionary Eusebio Francisco Kino first visited the Santa Cruz River valley in 1692.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] He founded the Mission San Xavier del Bac in 1700, about 7 mi (11 km) upstream from the site of the settlement of Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] A separate Convento settlement was founded downstream along the Santa Cruz River, near the base of what is now known as "A" mountain.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Hugo Oconór (Hugo O'Conor), the founding father of the city of Tucson, Arizona, authorized the construction of a military fort in that location, *Presidio San Agustín del Tucsón,* on August 20, 1775 (the present downtown Pima County Courthouse was built near this site).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] During the Spanish period of the presidio, attacks such as the Second Battle of Tucson were repeatedly mounted by the Apache.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Eventually, the town came to be called *Tucsón,* a Spanish version of the O'odham word for the area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] It was included in the state of Sonora after Mexico gained independence from the Kingdom of Spain and its Spanish Empire in 1821.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] During the Mexican–American War in 1846–1848, Tucsón was captured by Philip St.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] George Cooke with the Mormon Battalion, but it soon returned to Mexican control as Cooke proceeded to the west, establishing Cooke's Wagon Road to California.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucsón was not included in the Mexican Cession to the United States following the war.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Cooke's road through Tucsón became one of the important routes into California during the California Gold Rush of 1849.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The US acquired those portions of modern-day Arizona that lay south of the Gila River by treaty from Mexico in the Gadsden Purchase on June 8, 1854.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Under this treaty and purchase, Tucsón became a part of the United States of America.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The American military did not formally take over control until March 1856.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In time, the name of the town became standardized in English in its current form, where the stress is on the first syllable, the "u" is long, and the "c" is silent.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In 1857, Tucson was established as a stage station on the San Antonio–San Diego Mail Line.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In 1858, it became third division headquarters of the Butterfield Overland Mail and operated until the line was shut down in March 1861.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Overland Mail Corporation attempted to continue running, but following the Bascom Affair, devastating Apache attacks on the stations and coaches ended operations in August 1861.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In March 1861, a series of secession conventions were held throughout the region known as "Traditional Arizona", including in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Efforts by the Confederacy to secure control of the region led to the New Mexico Campaign.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Baylor sent Company A, Arizona Rangers to Tucson to protect the population from the Apache and delay the advance of Union troops from Fort Yuma.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] During the Civil War, the Tucson area saw several military engagements, primarily involving cavalry forces from the Union and Confederacy.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The most significant of these was the Battle of Picacho Pass on April 15, 1862.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Although the Confederate forces claimed a tactical victory at the pass, they were soon compelled to withdraw.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Union forces subsequently secured and held the territory, ensuring Union control of the region for the duration of the conflict.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] On May 20, 1862, Union forces entered Tucson and captured the city.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The city subsequently became part of the new Union Territory of Arizona.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson was incorporated in 1877, making it the oldest incorporated city in Arizona.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] From 1877 to 1878, the area suffered a rash of stagecoach robberies.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Most notable were the two holdups committed by masked road agent William Whitney Brazelton.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Brazelton held up two stages in the summer of 1878 near Point of Mountain Station, about 17 mi (27 km) northwest of Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] John Clum, of Tombstone, Arizona, fame, was one of the passengers.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Shibell and his citizen posse killed Brazelton on August 19, 1878, in a mesquite bosque along the Santa Cruz River 3 miles (5 km) south of Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Brazelton had been suspected of highway robbery in the Tucson area, the Prescott region, and the Silver City, New Mexico area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Because of the crimes and threats to his business, John J.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Valentine Sr. of Wells, Fargo & Co. had sent Bob Paul, a special agent and future Pima County sheriff, to investigate.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The US Army established Fort Lowell, then east of Tucson, to help protect settlers and travelers from Apache attacks.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In 1882, Morgan Earp was fatally shot, in what was later referred to in the press as the "Earp–Clanton Tragedy".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Marietta Spence, wife of Pete Spence, one of the Cochise County Cowboys, testified at the coroner's inquest on Earp's killing and implicated Frank Stilwell in the murder.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The coroner's jury concluded Pete Spence, Stilwell, Frederick Bode, and Florentino "Indian Charlie" Cruz were the prime suspects in the assassination of Morgan Earp.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Marshal Wyatt Earp gathered a few trusted friends and accompanied Virgil Earp and his family as they traveled to Benson to take a train to California.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] They found Stilwell apparently lying in wait for Virgil Earp at the Tucson station and killed Stilwell on the tracks.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] After killing Stilwell, Wyatt deputized others and conducted a vendetta, killing three more cowboys over the next few days before leaving the territory.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Jim Leavy had built a reputation of having fought in at least 16 gunfights.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] On June 5, 1882, Leavy had an argument with faro dealer John Murphy in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The two agreed to have a duel on the Mexican border, but after hearing of Leavy's exploits as a gunfighter, Murphy decided to ambush Leavy instead.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Together with two of his friends, Murphy ambushed Leavy as he was leaving the Palace Hotel, killing him.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] According to Wright, the three co-defendants in Leavy's murder later escaped from the Pima County Jail, but were later recaptured.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Murphy and Gibson were found in Fenner, California, living under assumed names; they were retried for the murder before being found not guilty.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Moyer was captured in Denver and sentenced to life in Yuma Territorial Prison, but was pardoned in 1888.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] As other settlers tried to overcome violent frontier society, in 1885, the territorial legislature founded the University of Arizona as a land-grant college on what was overgrazed ranchland between Tucson and Fort Lowell.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In 1890, Asians made up 4.2% of the city's population.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] They were predominantly Chinese men who had been recruited as workers on the railroads.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] By 1910, the population increased to 13,913.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Veterans Administration had begun construction of the present Veterans Hospital.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The city's clean, dry air made it a destination for many veterans who had been gassed in World War I and needed respiratory therapy.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In addition, these dry and high-altitude conditions were thought to be ideal for the treatment of tuberculosis, for which no cures were known before antibiotics were developed against it.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The city continued to grow, with the population increasing to 20,292 in 1920 and 36,818 in 1940.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In 2006, the estimated population of Pima County, in which Tucson is located, passed one million, while the City of Tucson's population was 535,000.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In 1912, Arizona was admitted as a state.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] This increased the number of flags that had been flown over Tucson to five: Spanish, Mexican, United States, Confederate, and the State of Arizona.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] During the territorial and early statehood periods, Tucson was Arizona's largest city and commercial center, while Phoenix was the seat of state government (beginning in 1889) and agriculture.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The development of Tucson Municipal Airport increased the city's prominence.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Between 1910 and 1920, though, Phoenix surpassed Tucson in population, and has continued to outpace Tucson in growth.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In recent years, both Tucson and Phoenix have had some of the highest growth rates of any jurisdiction in the United States.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, as of 2010, the City of Tucson has a land area of 226.71 sq mi (587.2 km2).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The city's elevation is 2,643 feet (806 m) above sea level (as measured at the Tucson International Airport).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson is on an alluvial plain in the Sonoran Desert, surrounded by five minor ranges of mountains: the Santa Catalina Mountains and the Tortolita Mountains to the north, the Santa Rita Mountains to the south, the Rincon Mountains to the east, and the Tucson Mountains to the west.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson Mountains include 4,687-foot (1,429 m) Wasson Peak.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The highest point in the area is Mount Wrightson, found in the Santa Rita Mountains at 9,453 feet (2,881 m) above sea level.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson is 116 mi (187 km) southeast of Phoenix and 64 mi (103 km) north of the United States–Mexico border by interstate highway.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The 2020 United States census puts the city's population at 542,629 with a metropolitan area population at 1,043,433.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In 2020, Tucson ranked as the 33rd-largest city and 53rd-largest metropolitan area in the United States.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] A major city in the Arizona Sun Corridor, Tucson is the largest city in southern Arizona, and the second-largest in the state after Phoenix.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] It is also the largest city in the area of the historic Gadsden Purchase.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] As of 2015, the Greater Tucson Metro area has exceeded a population of 1 million.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The city is built along the Santa Cruz River, formerly a perennial river.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Now a dry riverbed for much of the year, it regularly floods during significant seasonal rains.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Interstate 10 runs northwest through town, connecting Tucson to Phoenix to the northwest (on the way to its western terminus in Santa Monica, California), and to Las Cruces, New Mexico and El Paso, Texas to the southeast.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] (Its eastern terminus is in Jacksonville, Florida).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] I-19 runs south from Tucson to Nogales and the Mexico–United States border.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] I-19 is the only Interstate Highway in the United States that uses Mexico's "kilometer posts" instead of "mileposts".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] However, speed limits are marked in "miles per hour".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Similar to many other cities in the Western US, Tucson was developed by European Americans on a grid plan starting in the late 19th century, with the city center at Stone Avenue and Broadway Boulevard.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] While this intersection was initially near the geographic center of Tucson, the center has shifted as the city has expanded far to the east.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Development to the west was effectively blocked by the Tucson Mountains.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Covering a large geographic area, Tucson has many distinct neighborhoods.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] At the end of the 2010s, city planners and the business community worked to redevelop downtown Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The primary project was Rio Nuevo, a large retail and community center that had been stalled in planning for more than a decade.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] One Rio Nuevo project that was successful is Mission Garden.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Related to Tucson's City of Gastronomy designation, this living agricultural museum at the base of Sentinel Peak west of downtown grows heritage crops and heirloom trees that represent people who have lived in the area for thousands of years.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Downtown is generally regarded as the area bordered by 17th Street to the south, I-10 to the west, and 6th Street to the north, and Toole Avenue and the Union Pacific (formerly Southern Pacific) railroad tracks, site of the historic train depot on the east side.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Downtown is divided into the Presidio District, the Barrio Viejo, and the Congress Street Arts and Entertainment District.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Some authorities include the 4th Avenue shopping district, northeast of the rest of downtown and connected by an underpass beneath the UPRR tracks.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Historic attractions downtown with rich architecture include the Hotel Congress designed in 1919, the Art Deco Fox Theatre designed in 1929, the Rialto Theatre opened in 1920, and St.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Included on the National Register of Historic Places is the old Pima County Courthouse, designed by Roy Place in 1928.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] El Charro Café, Tucson's oldest restaurant, operates its main location downtown.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] As one of the oldest parts of town, Central Tucson is anchored by the Broadway Village shopping center, designed by local architect Josias Joesler at the intersection of Broadway Boulevard and Country Club Road.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The 4th Avenue Shopping District between downtown, the university, and the Lost Barrio just east of downtown, also has many unique and popular stores.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Local retail business in Central Tucson is densely concentrated along Fourth Avenue and the Main Gate Square on University Boulevard near the UA campus.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] El Con Mall is also in the eastern part of midtown.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The University of Arizona, chartered in 1885, is in midtown and includes Arizona Stadium and McKale Center (named for J.F.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] "Pop" McKale, a prominent coach and athletics administrator at the university).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The historic Tucson High School (designed by Roy Place in 1924) was featured in the 1987 film *Can't Buy Me Love*.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Arizona Inn (built in 1930) and the Tucson Botanical Gardens are also in Central Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson's largest park, Reid Park, is in midtown and includes Reid Park Zoo and Hi Corbett Field.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Speedway Boulevard, a major east–west arterial road in central Tucson, was named the "ugliest street in America" by *Life* in the early 1970s, quoting Tucson Mayor James Corbett.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In the late 1990s, Speedway Boulevard was awarded "Street of the Year" by *Arizona Highways.* Speedway Boulevard was named after an historic horse racetrack, known as the Harlem River Speedway, and more commonly called "The Speedway", in New York City.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Tucson street was called "The Speedway" from 1904 to about 1906, when "The" was removed from the title.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] As of the early 21st century, Central Tucson is considered bicycle-friendly.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] To the east of the University of Arizona, Third Street is bike-only except for local traffic; it passes by the historic homes of the Sam Hughes neighborhood.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] To the west, East University Boulevard leads to the Fourth Avenue Shopping District.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] To the North, North Mountain Avenue has a full bike-only lane for half of the 3.5 miles (5.6 km) to the Rillito River Park bike and walk multi-use path.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] To the south, North Highland Avenue leads to the Barraza-Aviation Parkway bicycle path.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] South Tucson is the name of an independent, incorporated town of 1 sq mi (2.6 km2) south of downtown.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] It is surrounded by the City of Tucson and was incorporated in 1936 and reincorporated in 1940.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The population is about 83% Mexican-American and 10% Native American, as residents self-identify in the census.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] South Tucson is widely known for its many Mexican restaurants and architectural styles.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Bright murals have been painted on some walls, but city policy discourages this and many have been painted over.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The south side of the city of Tucson is generally considered to be the area around 25 sq mi (65 km2) south of 22nd Street, east of I-19, west of Davis Monthan Air Force Base and southwest of Aviation Parkway, and north of Los Reales Road.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Tucson International Airport and Tucson Electric Park are located here.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The West Side has areas of both urban and suburban development.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] It is generally defined as the area west of I-10.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Western Tucson encompasses the banks of the Santa Cruz River and the foothills of the Tucson Mountains.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Area attractions include the International Wildlife Museum and Sentinel Peak.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Marriott Starr Pass Resort and Spa serves travelers and residents.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] As travelers pass the Tucson Mountains, they enter the area commonly referred to as "west of" Tucson or "Old West Tucson".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In this large, undulating plain extending south into the Altar Valley, rural residential development predominates.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Attractions include Saguaro National Park West, and movie set/theme park developed at the Old Tucson Studios.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] On Sentinel Peak, just west of downtown, a giant "A" was installed in honor of the University of Arizona, resulting in the nickname "A" Mountain.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Starting in about 1915, an annual tradition developed for freshmen to whitewash the A, which was visible for miles.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] After the September 11 terrorist attacks, the A was painted red, white, and blue.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] At the beginning of the Iraq War in 2003, antiwar activists painted the A black.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Competition ensued, with various sides repainting the A in different colors until the city council intervened and made the red, white, and blue colors official.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In 2013, the color scheme changed back to white.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Another color may be decided by a biennial election.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] With the tricolor scheme, some observers complain the shape of the A is hard to distinguish from the background of the peak.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Since 1993, the A has been painted green for St.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] It has also been given other color schemes for different causes.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] North Tucson includes the urban neighborhoods of Amphitheater and Flowing Wells.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Usually considered the area north of Fort Lowell Road, North Tucson includes some of Tucson's primary commercial zones (Tucson Mall and the Oracle Road Corridor).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Many of the city's most upscale boutiques, restaurants, and art galleries are also on the north side, including St.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The plaza is directly adjacent to the historic St.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Philip's in the Hills Episcopal Church (built in 1936).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The north side also is home to the suburban community of Catalina Foothills, in the foothills of the Santa Catalina Mountains just north of the city limits.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] This community includes many of the area's most expensive homes, sometimes multimillion-dollar estates.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Foothills area is generally defined as north of River Road, east of Oracle Road and west of Sabino Creek.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Some of the Tucson area's major resorts are in the Catalina Foothills, including Hacienda Del Sol, Westin La Paloma Resort, Loews Ventana Canyon Resort and Canyon Ranch Resort.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] La Encantada, an outdoor shopping mall, is also in the Foothills.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The DeGrazia Gallery of the Sun is near the intersection of Swan Road and Skyline Drive.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Built by artist Ted DeGrazia starting in 1951, the 10-acre (4.0 ha) property is listed on the National Register of Historic Places and features an eclectic chapel, an art gallery, and a museum.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Continental Ranch (Marana), Dove Mountain (Marana), and Rancho Vistoso (Oro Valley), and Saddlebrooke (North Oro Valley) are all master planned communities in the northwest that have thousands of residents.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The community of Casas Adobes is also on the Northwest side, with the distinction of being Tucson's first suburb, established in the late 1940s.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Casas Adobes is centered on the historic Casas Adobes Plaza (built in 1948).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Casas Adobes is also home to Tohono Chul Park, which is now within the town of Oro Valley, (a nature preserve) near the intersection of North Oracle Road and West Ina Road.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The attempted assassination of Representative Gabby Giffords, which resulted in the murders of chief judge for the U.S.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] District Court for Arizona, John Roll, and five other people on January 8, 2011, occurred at the La Toscana Village in Casas Adobes.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Foothills Mall is also on the northwest side in Casas Adobes.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] This area is home to many of the Tucson area's golf courses and resorts, including the Preserve and Mountainview Golf Clubs at Saddlebrooke, Hilton El Conquistador Golf & Tennis Resort in Oro Valley, the Omni Tucson National Resort & Spa, and Westward Look Resort.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Ritz Carlton at Dove Mountain, the second Ritz Carlton resort in Arizona, which also includes a golf course, opened in the foothills of the Tortolita Mountains in northeast Marana in 2009.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] East Tucson is relatively new compared to other parts of the city, developed between the 1950s and the 1970s, with developments such as Desert Palms Park.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] It is generally classified as the area of the city east of Swan Road, with above-average real estate values relative to the rest of the city.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The area includes urban and suburban development near the Rincon Mountains.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] East Tucson includes Saguaro National Park East.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson's "Restaurant Row" is also on the east side, along with a significant corporate and financial presence.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Restaurant Row is sandwiched by three of Tucson's storied Vicinages: Harold Bell Wright Estates, named after the author's ranch which occupied some of that area before the depression; the Tucson Country Club (the third to bear the name Tucson Country Club), and the Dorado Country Club.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson's largest office building is 5151 East Broadway in east Tucson, completed in 1975.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The first phases of Williams Centre, a mixed-use, master-planned development on Broadway near Craycroft Road, were opened in 1987.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Park Place, a recently renovated shopping center, is also along Broadway (west of Wilmot Road).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Near the intersection of Craycroft and Ft.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Lowell Roads are the remnants of the Historic Fort Lowell.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] This area has become one of Tucson's iconic neighborhoods.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In 1891, the Fort was abandoned and much of the interior was stripped of their useful components and it quickly fell into ruin.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In 1900, three of the officer buildings were purchased for use as a sanitarium.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The sanitarium was then sold to Harvey Adkins in 1928.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Bolsius family – Pete, Nan and Charles – purchased and renovated surviving adobe buildings of the Fort, transforming them into spectacular artistic southwestern architectural examples.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Their woodwork, plaster treatment and sense of proportion drew on their Dutch heritage and New Mexican experience.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Other artists and academics throughout the middle of the 20th century, including Win Ellis, Jack Maul, Madame Germaine Cheruy and René Cheruy, Giorgio Belloli, Charles Bode, Veronica Hughart, Edward H.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Spicer and Rosamond Spicer, Hazel Larson Archer and Ruth Brown, renovated adobes, built homes and lived in the area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The artist colony attracted writers and poets including beat generation Alan Harrington and Jack Kerouac whose visit is documented in his iconic book *On the Road*.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] This rural pocket in the middle of the city is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Each year in February the vicinage celebrates its history in the City Landmark it owns and restored the San Pedro Chapel.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Situated between the Santa Catalina Mountains and the Rincon Mountains near Redington Pass northeast of the city limits is the affluent community of Tanque Verde.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Arizona National Golf Club, Forty-Niners Country Club, and the historic Tanque Verde Guest Ranch are also in northeast Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Southeast Tucson continues to experience rapid residential development.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The area includes Davis-Monthan Air Force Base.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The area is considered to be south of Golf Links Road.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] It is the home of Santa Rita High School, Chuck Ford Park (Lakeside Park), Lakeside Lake, Lincoln Park (upper and lower), The Lakecrest Vicinagess, and Pima Community College East Campus.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The Atterbury Wash with its access to excellent bird watching is also in the Southeast Tucson area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The suburban community of Rita Ranch houses many of the military families from Davis-Monthan, and is near the southeasternmost expansion of the current city limits.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Close by Rita Ranch and also within the city limits lies Civano, a planned development meant to showcase ecologically sound building practices and lifestyles.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson has a hot desert climate (Köppen: *BWh*), with two major seasons, a hot summer and mild winter.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson averages 10.61 inches (269.5 mm) of precipitation per year, concentrated during the Pacific storms of winter and the North American Monsoon of summer.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Fall and spring tend to be sunny and dry.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Despite being at a more southerly latitude than Phoenix, Tucson is slightly cooler and wetter due to a variety of factors, including elevation and orographic lift in surrounding mountains, though Tucson does occasionally see warmer daytime temperatures in the winter.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Summer is characterized by average daily high temperatures between 98 and 102 °F (37 and 39 °C) and low temperatures between 71 and 77 °F (22 and 25 °C).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Early summer is characterized by low humidity and clear skies; mid- and late summer are characterized by higher humidity, cloudy skies, and frequent rain.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The sun is intense in Tucson during part of the year, and those who spend time outdoors need protection.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Recent studies show that the rate of skin cancer in Arizona is at least three times higher than in more northerly regions.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Additionally, heat stroke is a concern for hikers, mountain bikers, and adventurers who explore canyons, open desert lands, and other exposed areas.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] While monsoon season officially begins on June 15, the arrival of the North American Monsoon is unpredictable, as it varies from year to year.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] On average, Tucson receives its first monsoon storms around July 3.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Monsoon activity generally persists through August and often into September.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] During the monsoon, the humidity is much higher than the rest of the year.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] It begins with clouds building up from the south in the early afternoon, followed by intense thunderstorms and rainfall, which can cause flash floods.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The evening sky at this time of year is often pierced with dramatic lightning strikes.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Large areas of the city do not have storm sewers, so monsoon rains flood the main thoroughfares, usually for no longer than a few hours.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] A few underpasses in Tucson have "feet of water" scales painted on their supports to discourage fording by automobiles during a rainstorm.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Arizona traffic code Title 28–910, the so-called "Stupid Motorist Law", was instituted in 1995 to discourage people from entering flooded roadways.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] If the road is flooded and a barricade is in place, motorists who drive around the barricade can be charged up to $2,000 for costs involved in rescuing them.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Despite the warnings and precautions, three Tucson drivers have drowned between 2004 and 2010.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The weather in the fall is much like spring, dry, with warm/cool nights and warm/hot days.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Temperatures above 100 °F (38 °C) are possible into early October.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Temperatures decline at the quickest rate in October and November, and are normally the coolest in late December and early January.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Winters in Tucson are mild relative to other parts of the United States.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Average daytime highs range between 65 and 70 °F (18 and 21 °C), with overnight lows between 40 and 44 °F (4 and 7 °C).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson typically averages three hard freezes per winter season, with temperatures dipping to the mid- or low 20 degrees F (−4 to −7 °C), but this is typically limited to only a very few nights.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Although rare, snow occasionally falls in lower elevations in Tucson and is common in the Santa Catalina Mountains.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The most recent snowfall was on March 2, 2023, when a winter storm caused snow to fall throughout most of the southwest.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tucson airport recorded 1.0 in (2.5 cm) of snow, the seventh heaviest March snowfall on record.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Early spring is characterized by gradually rising temperatures and several weeks of vivid wildflower blooms beginning in late February and into March.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] During this time of year the diurnal temperature variation occurs with a temperature change often surpassing 30 °F (17 °C) daily.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Since records began in 1894, the record maximum temperature was 117 °F (47 °C) on June 27, 1990, and the record minimum temperature was 6 °F (−14 °C) on January 7, 1913.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] There are an average of 158 days annually with highs of 90 °F (32 °C) or higher and an average of 12 days with lows reaching or below the freezing mark.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Average annual precipitation is 10.61 in (269 mm).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] On average, 47.4 days have measurable precipitation.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The most precipitation in one month was 8.06 in (205 mm) in July 2021.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The most precipitation in 24 hours was 3.93 in (100 mm) on July 29, 1958.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Annual snowfall averages 0.1 in (0.25 cm).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The most snow in one winter was 6.8 in (17 cm) in winter 1971–1972.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The most snow in one month was 6.8 in (17 cm) in December 1971.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The population density was 2,500.1 inhabitants per square mile (965.3 inhabitants/km2).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The 209,609 dwelling units had an average density of 1,076.7 per square mile (415.7/km2).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 69.7% White (down from 94.8% in 1970), 5.0% Black or African-American, 2.7% Native American, 2.9% Asian, 0.2% Pacific Islander, 16.9% from other races, and 3.8% from two or more races.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Hispanics or Latinos of any race were 41.6% of the population.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Non-Hispanic Whites were 47.2% of the population in 2010, down from 72.8% in 1970.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The largest ancestries reported in Tucson according to 2022 estimates were Mexican (39.9%), German (11%), English (7.7%), Italian (3.4%), American (2.8%), and Polish (1.8%).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] According to research by demographer William H.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Frey using data from the 2010 United States census, Tucson has the lowest level of Black-White segregation of any of the 100 largest metropolitan areas in the United States.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Of the 192,891 households, 29.0% had children under 18 living with them, 39.7% were married couples living together, 13.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 41.7% were not families.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] About 32.3% of all households were made up of individuals, and 9.3% had someone living alone who was 65 or older.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The average household size was 2.42, and the average family size was 3.12.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] For every 100 females, there were 96.0 males.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] For every 100 females 18 and over, there were 93.3 males.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The median income for a household in the city was $30,981, and for a family was $37,344.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Males had a median income of $28,548 versus $23,086 for females.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The per capita income for the city was $16,322.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] About 13.7% of families and 18.4% of the population were below the poverty line, including 23.6% of those under 18 and 11.0% of those 65 or over.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Much of Tucson's economic development has centered on the development of the University of Arizona, which is the city's largest employer.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Davis-Monthan Air Force Base, on the city's southeastern edge, also provides many jobs for Tucson residents.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Its presence, as well as the presence of the US Army Intelligence Center (Fort Huachuca, the region's largest employer, in nearby Sierra Vista), has led to the development of many high-technology industries, including government contractors.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The city of Tucson is also a major hub for the Union Pacific Railroad's Sunset Route that links the Los Angeles ports with the South/Southeast regions of the country.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Raytheon Missiles and Defense (formerly Hughes Aircraft Co.), Texas Instruments, IBM, Intuit Inc., Universal Avionics, Honeywell Aerospace, Sunquest Information Systems, Sanofi-Aventis, Ventana Medical Systems, Inc., and Bombardier Aerospace all have a large presence in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Roughly 150 Tucson companies are involved in the design and manufacture of optics and optoelectronics systems, earning Tucson the nickname "Optics Valley".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Much of this comes from the Steward Observatory at the University of Arizona, which is one of few locations in the world that can cast the enormous mirrors used in telescopes around the world and in space.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Tourism is another major industry in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] The city's many resorts, hotels, and attractions bring in $2 billion and over 3.5 million visitors annually.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] One of the major annual attractions is the Tucson Gem and Mineral Show, and its associated shows, all held generally in the first two weeks of February.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] These associated shows (such as gems, jewelry, beads, and fossils) are held throughout the city, with 43 different shows in 2010.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] This makes Tucson's the largest such exposition in the world.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Its yearly economic impact in 2015 was evaluated at $120 million.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] In addition to vacationers, many winter residents, or "snowbirds", are attracted to Tucson's mild winters and live here on a seasonal basis.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] They also contribute to the local economy.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p01] Snowbirds often purchase second homes in Tucson and nearby areas, contributing significantly to the property tax base.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Tucson Gem & Mineral Show is one of the largest gem and mineral shows in the world and has been held for over 50 years.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The show is only one part of the gem, mineral, fossil and bead gathering held across more than 45 different sites in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The shows run from late January to mid-February, with the official show lasting two weeks in February.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Since 2009, the Tucson Festival of Books has been held annually over a two-day period in March at the University of Arizona.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] By 2010 it had become the fourth largest book festival in the United States, with 450 authors and 80,000 attendees.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In addition to readings and lectures, it features a science fair, varied entertainment, food, and exhibitors ranging from local retailers and publishers to regional and national nonprofit organizations.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] El Tour de Tucson is a cycling race that has taken place in Tucson since 1983.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The race tends to happen in the month of November, before American Thanksgiving.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] There are a number of distances available to ride, from 1-mile (1.6 km) fun rides to a long-distance ride that spans the whole city, resulting in 102 miles (164 km).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In addition to being a competitive race, this race also allows non-profit charities to raise funds for their organizations.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The race was first held by the Perimeter Bicycling Association in 1983 with less than 200 cyclists, and raised $4,500; by 2023 there have been close to 9,000 cyclists and raised $5.8 million.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Recognition comes from USA Today, naming El Tour de Tucson a top-10 road race in the United States every year since 2023, ranking at #8 in 2026.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] For the past 33 years, the Tucson Folk Festival has taken place the first Saturday and Sunday of May in downtown Tucson's El Presidio Park.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In addition to nationally known headline acts each evening, the Festival highlights over 100 local and regional musicians on five stages and is one of the largest free festivals in the country.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] All stages are within easy walking distance.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Organized by the Tucson Kitchen Musicians' Association, volunteers make this festival possible.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] KXCI 91.3-FM, Arizona's only community radio station, is a major partner, broadcasting from the Plaza Stage throughout the weekend.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] There are also many workshops, events for children, sing-alongs, and a popular singer-songwriter contest.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Musicians typically play 30-minute sets, supported by professional audio staff volunteers.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] A variety of food and crafts are available at the festival, as well as local microbrews.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] All proceeds help fund future festivals.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] There are two Fourth Avenue Street Fairs, in December and late March/early April, staged between 9th Street and University Boulevard, that feature arts and crafts booths, food vendors and street performers.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The fairs began in 1970 when Fourth Avenue, which at the time had half a dozen thrift shops, several New Age bookshops and the Food Conspiracy Co-Op, was a gathering place for hippies, and a few merchants put tables in front of their stores to attract customers before the holidays.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] These days, the street fair has grown into a large corporate event, with most tables owned by outside merchants.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] It hosts mostly traveling craftsmen selling various arts such as pottery, paintings, wood working, metal decorations, candles, and many others.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Another popular event held in February, which is early spring in Tucson, is the Fiesta de los Vaqueros, or rodeo week, founded by winter visitor, Leighton Kramer.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] While at its heart the Fiesta is a sporting event, it includes what is billed as "the world's largest non-mechanized parade".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Rodeo Parade is a popular event as most schools give two rodeo days off instead of Presidents' Day.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The exception is Presidio High (a non-public charter school), which does not get either.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Western wear is seen throughout the city as corporate dress codes are cast aside during the Fiesta.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Fiesta de los Vaqueros marks the beginning of the rodeo season in the United States.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Every October for the past 30 years, the Tucson Meet Yourself festival has celebrated the city's many ethnic groups.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] For one weekend, the downtown area features dancing, singing, artwork, and food from more than 30 different ethnicities.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The event is held at and around the Jacome Plaza, located in front of the Joel D.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] All performers are from Tucson and the surrounding area, in keeping with the idea of "meeting yourself".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The records of the Tucson Meet Yourself Festival reside at the University of Arizona Special Collections Library.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Since 2012, during the first two weekends of October, the Tucson Historic Preservation Foundation hosts Tucson Modernism Week.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The event includes more than 30 programs including tours, lectures, exhibits, films and parties.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The All Souls Procession, held in early November, is one of Tucson's largest festivals.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Modeled on the Mexican holiday Dia de los Muertos (Day of the Dead), it combines aspects of many different cultural traditions.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The first All Souls Procession was organized by local artist Susan Kay Johnson in 1990 and involved 35 participants; by 2013, participation was estimated at 50,000.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Procession, held at sundown, consists of a non-motorized parade through downtown Tucson featuring many floats, sculptures, and memorials, in which the community is encouraged to participate.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The parade is followed by performances on an outdoor stage, culminating in the burning of an urn in which written prayers have been collected from participants and spectators.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The event is organized and funded by the non-profit arts organization Many Mouths One Stomach, with the help of volunteers and donations from the public and local businesses.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Cyclovia Tucson is an annual event supported by Living Streets Alliance that invites people of all ages and abilities to walk, bike, and roll down car-free streets for a day.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Cyclovia is an Open Streets initiative designed to maximize the enormous amount of space taken up by roads in sprawling cities like Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Since 2010, Cyclovia transforms the streets of metro Tucson into a block party atmosphere to socialize, incorporating partnerships with small businesses, and giving people the opportunity to move freely through the streets without moving cars.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Cyclovia happens twice a year, typically in the spring and in the fall.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Fourth Avenue, near the University of Arizona, is home to many shops, restaurants, and bars, and hosts the annual 4th Avenue Street Fair every December and March.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] University Boulevard, leading directly to the UA Main Gate, is also the center of numerous bars, retail shops, and restaurants most commonly frequented by the large student population of the UA.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] El Tiradito is a religious shrine in the downtown area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The shrine dates back to the early days of Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] It is based on a love story of revenge and murder.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] People stop by the shrine to light a candle for someone in need, a place for people to go give hope.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Biosphere 2 is a 3.14-acre (1.27 ha) educational facility designed to mimic a tropical or sub-tropical climate-controlled environment.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The accomplished and awarded writers (poets, novelists, dramatists, nonfiction writers) who have lived in Tucson include Edward Abbey, Erskine Caldwell, Barbara Kingsolver, Joy Williams, Leslie Marmon Silko, and David Foster Wallace.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Some were associated with the University of Arizona, but many were independent writers who chose to make Tucson their home.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The city is particularly active in publishing and presenting contemporary innovative poetry in various ways.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Examples are the Chax Press, a publisher of poetry books in trade and book arts editions, and the University of Arizona Poetry Center, which has a sizable poetry library and presents readings, conferences, and workshops.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Theater groups include the Arizona Theatre Company, which performs in the Temple of Music and Art, and Arizona Onstage Productions, a not-for-profit theater company devoted to musical theater.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Broadway in Tucson presents the touring reproductions of many Broadway-style events.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Gaslight Theater produces musical melodrama parodies in the old Jerry Lewis Theater and has been in Tucson since 1977.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is home to the Tucson Symphony Orchestra, the oldest performing arts organization in the state of Arizona.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Ballet Tucson is the only professional ballet company in Southern Arizona.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The company typically has five productions per year, including The Nutcracker with live accompaniment from Tucson Symphony Orchestra.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The annual Tucson Fringe Festival, held in various local venues in and around Downtown Tucson, offers non-traditional artistic performances at low cost to the public.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The festival is held in early January each year.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Musical organizations include the Tucson Symphony Orchestra (founded in 1929) and Arizona Opera (founded as the Tucson Opera Company in 1971).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Tucson Arizona Boys Chorus, founded in 1939 and performing a wide-ranging repertoire that incorporates rope tricks, has represented the city as "Ambassadors in Levi's" at local, national, and international concerts.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Tucson Girls Chorus runs six choirs and numerous satellite choirs which perform locally, nationally, and internationally.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is considered an influential center for Mariachi music and is home to a large number of Mariachi musicians and singers.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Tucson International Mariachi Conference, hosted annually since 1982, involves several hundred mariachi bands and folklorica dance troops during a three-day festival in April.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Norteño Festival and Street Fair in the enclave city of South Tucson is held annually at the end of summer.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is also known nationally for its punk scene.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Since the late 1970s punk subculture has flourished in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] At present there are multiple punk bars downtown and house venues in the surrounding neighborhoods.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Prominent musicians based in Tucson or with ties to the city include Linda Ronstadt, Lalo Guerrero, The Dusty Chaps, Howe Gelb, Bob Log III, Calexico, Giant Sand, Hipster Daddy-O and the Handgrenades, The Bled, AJJ, Ramshackle Glory, and Tucson's official troubadour Ted Ramirez.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Tucson Area Music Awards, or TAMMIES, are an annual event.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson has been the setting and filming location for multiple films.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Some notable films that have been filmed in Tucson include *Revenge of the Nerds*, *Can't Buy Me Love*, *Major League*, *Tombstone*, and *Tin Cup*.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The city is also a common filming location and setting for Western films, most were filmed at Old Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The television show *Hey Dude* was filmed at Tanque Verde Ranch.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Additionally, the fictional motorcycle clubs the Sons of Anarchy and Mayans from the television shows *Sons of Anarchy* and *Mayans M.C.* both have Tucson chapters that are featured in the show.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In the season 4 *Sons of Anarchy* episode "Una Venta", the cast travels to Tucson to discuss an issue with the Tucson chapter.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The upcoming TV series *Duster* began filming in Tucson in October 2021.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The series is specifically being filmed in downtown Tucson and the Tucson Mountains region of Saguaro National Park.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is well known for its Sonoran-style Mexican food.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Since the turn of the century, other ethnic restaurants and fine dining choices have proliferated.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson cuisine is influenced by a diverse group of peoples, from Native Americans to Spanish settlers, Anglo-American ranchers and rail workers from China.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In 2015, the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) designated Tucson a "world city of gastronomy" under the Creative Cities Network program, becoming thus the first city of gastronomy in the United States.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The city's focus on food includes Mission Garden, a living agricultural museum that showcases the crops and trees that have been grown in the area for over 4,000 years.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Sonoran hot dog is very popular in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] A hot dog is wrapped in bacon and grilled, served on a bolillo-style hot dog bun, and topped with pinto beans, onions, tomatoes, and a variety of additional condiments, often including mayonnaise, mustard, and jalapeño salsa.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson also has a strong, though contested, claim to being the place of origin of the chimichanga.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is also the birthplace of Chinese Chorizo, a Sino-Mexican fusion dish consisting of pork sausage seasoned with soy sauce, rice wine and chili.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] This version of chorizo originated from local Chinese grocery stores, which existed from the 1880s to 1970s.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Since 2022, the Chinese Chorizo Festival has been held every October, and participants invent new dishes involving the sausage.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is commonly known as "The Old Pueblo".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] While the exact origin of this nickname is uncertain, it is commonly traced back to Mayor R.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] When rail service was established to the city on March 20, 1880, Leatherwood celebrated the fact by sending telegrams to various leaders, including the President of the United States and the Pope, announcing the "ancient and honorable pueblo" of Tucson was now connected by rail to the outside world.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The term became popular with newspaper writers who often abbreviated it as "A. and H.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] This in turn transformed into the current form of "The Old Pueblo".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In the early 1980s, city leaders ran a contest searching for a new nickname.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The winning entry was the "Sunshine Factory".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The new nickname never gained popular acceptance, allowing the old name to remain in common use.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson was dubbed "Optics Valley" in 1992 when *Business Week* ran a cover story on the Arizona Optics Industry Association.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is not represented in any of the five major sports leagues of the United States: the NFL, MLB, the NBA, the NHL, or MLS.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The University of Arizona's athletic teams, most notably the men's basketball, football, baseball, and softball teams, have strong local interest.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The men's basketball team, formerly coached by Hall of Fame head coach Lute Olson and currently coached by Tommy Lloyd, made 25 straight NCAA Tournaments appearances (1985–2009) and won the 1997 National Championship.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Arizona's softball team has reached the NCAA National Championship game 12 times and has won 8 times, most recently in 2007.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Arizona's baseball team won NCAA National Championships in 1976, 1980, 1986, and 2012.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The university's swim teams have gained international recognition, with swimmers coming from as far as Japan and Africa to train with coach Frank Busch, who has also worked with the U.S.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Both men's and women's swim teams won the 2008 NCAA National Championships.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In ice hockey, the Tucson Roadrunners of the American Hockey League began play during the 2016–2017 season after relocating to Tucson in 2016.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] They play at the Tucson Convention Center Arena from October to April, and are the top affiliate of the Utah Mammoth.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Between 1975 and 1979, there were three professional ice hockey teams in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Tucson Mavericks of the Central Hockey League from 1975 to 1976, the Tucson Icemen of the Southwest Hockey League from 1976 to 1977, and the Tucson Rustlers of the Pacific Hockey League from 1978 to 1979.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Later in 1997, the Tucson Gila Monsters were unveiled and played from 1997 to 1999 in the West Coast Hockey League.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] After the Gila Monsters folded in 1999 a team was announced that were to begin play for the Western Professional Hockey League called the Tucson Scorch they never played a game due to the owner not posting a financial guarantee which was required for a team to begin play in the league.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In American football, the Indoor Football League announced in 2018 they were bringing an expansion team to Tucson to play at the Tucson Convention Center's newly renovated Tucson Arena starting in 2019.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] That team would be announced as the Tucson Sugar Skulls.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In baseball, the Tucson Saguaros of the independent Pecos League began play in 2016 and play at the Kino Veterans Memorial Stadium.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] They won the league in their inaugural season and won two more championships in 2020 and 2021.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] A team in the Mexican Pacific League moved to Tucson in 2025, although, due to visa issues, it has yet to play a game in its intended home of Kino Veterans Memorial Stadium.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Tucson Padres played at Kino Veterans Memorial Stadium from 2011 to 2013.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] They served as the AAA affiliate of the San Diego Padres.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The team, formerly known as the Portland Beavers, temporarily moved to Tucson from Portland while the team awaited a new stadium in Escondido.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Legal issues derailed the plans to build the Escondido stadium, so they moved to El Paso, Texas for the 2014 season and onward.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Previously, the Tucson Sidewinders, a triple-A affiliate of the Arizona Diamondbacks from 1998 to 2008, won the Pacific Coast League championship and unofficial AAA championship in 2006.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Sidewinders played at Tucson Electric Park (now called Kino Sports Complex) and were in the Pacific Conference South of the PCL.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Sidewinders were sold in 2007 and moved to Reno, Nevada after the 2008 season.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] They now compete as the Reno Aces, who have served as a triple-A affiliate for the Arizona Diamondbacks since 2009.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In soccer, Tucson is host to the Mobile Mini Sun Cup, the largest pre-season Major League Soccer (MLS) tournament in the country.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] As many as 11 MLS soccer clubs train in Tucson every winter.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is also host to FC Tucson, a professional soccer club that plays at the Kino Sports Complex North Stadium in the third-tier USL League Two.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The United States Handball Association Hall of Fame is in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tracks include Tucson Raceway Park and Rillito Downs.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson Raceway Park hosts NASCAR-sanctioned auto racing events and is one of only two asphalt short tracks in Arizona.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Rillito Downs is an in-town destination on weekends in January and February each year.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] This historic track held the first organized quarter horse races in the world, and they are still racing there.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The racetrack is threatened by development.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Moltacqua racetrack, was another historic horse racetrack on what is now Sabino Canyon Road and Vactor Ranch Trail, but it no longer exists.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The city has more than 120 parks, from small and local to larger parks with ballfields, natural areas, lakes, 5 public golf courses, and Reid Park Zoo.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Loop is a popular system of shared-use paths encircling the city primarily along washes and is usually well-separated from traffic.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Several scenic parks and points of interest are also nearby, including the Tucson Botanical Gardens, Tohono Chul Park, Saguaro National Park, Sabino Canyon, and Biosphere 2 (just north of the city, near the town of Oracle).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tumamoc Hill is an active research site maintained by the University of Arizona and Pima County that doubles as a popular walking/running trail.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The paved trail on Tumamoc Hill is 1.5 miles (2.4 km) each way, divided into two parts.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The lower half is a much more gradual slope compared to the steep upper half reaching a final elevation of 2,340 ft (710 m), where it overlooks most of the city of Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The trail attracts around 1,500 visits a day from various demographics of the Tucson area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Lemmon is 25 miles (40 km) north (by the Catalina Highway) and over 6,700 feet (2,000 m) above Tucson in the Santa Catalina Mountains in the Coronado National Forest.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Outdoor activities in the Catalinas include hiking, mountain biking, birding, rock climbing, picnicking, camping, swimming in mountain stream pools, sky rides at Ski Valley, fishing, and photography.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In winter with enough snow, the sky ride converts back to skiing at the southernmost ski resort in the continental United States.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Summerhaven, a community near the top of Mt.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The League of American Bicyclists gave Tucson a gold rating for bicycle friendliness in late April 2007.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson hosts the largest perimeter cycling event in the United States.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The ride, called "El Tour de Tucson", takes place each November on the Saturday before Thanksgiving.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] El Tour de Tucson produced and promoted by Perimeter Bicycling has had as many as 10,000 participants from all over the world.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In 2019, ridership is expected to be 6,000 cyclists.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is one of only nine cities in the U.S. to receive a gold rating or higher for cycling friendliness from the League of American Bicyclists.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The city is known for its winter cycling opportunities, with teams and riders from around the world spending a portion of the year training in Tucson's year-round biking climate.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Popular mountain biking areas include Tucson Mountain Park, Sweetwater Preserve, the Tortolita Mountain trail systems, and Fantasy Island.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Road cyclists take on Catalina Highway's steep climb year-round.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Pima County supported John Kerry 53% to 47% in the 2004 U.S.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Presidential Election, and Barack Obama 54% to 46% in the 2008 U.S.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In the latter year, Pima was the only county to vote against Arizona's gay marriage ban.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In 2013, Tucson became the second city in Arizona to approve of civil unions for same-sex partners.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The city was the first in the state to pass a domestic partnership registry earlier in 2003.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In general, Tucson and Pima County support the Democratic Party, while the state's largest metropolitan area, greater Phoenix, has traditionally supported the Republican Party.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Congressional redistricting in 2013, following the publication of the 2010 Census, divided the Tucson area into three Federal Congressional districts (the first, second and third of Arizona).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The United States Postal Service operates post offices in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Tucson Main Post Office is at 1501 South Cherrybell Stravenue.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson follows the "weak mayor" model of the council-manager form of local government.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The six-member city council holds exclusive legislative authority, and shares executive authority with the mayor, who is elected by the voters independently of the council.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] An appointed city manager is responsible for the day-to-day operations of the city.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is the only city in Arizona that holds officially partisan elections for city offices, with candidates nominated through party primaries.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Both the council members and the mayor serve four-year terms; none face term limits.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Council members are nominated by their wards via a ward-level primary held in August.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The top vote-earners from each party then compete at-large for their ward's seat on the November ballot.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In other words, on election day the whole city votes on all the council races up for that year.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Council elections are severed: Wards 1, 2, and 4 (as well as the mayor) are up for election in the same year (most recently 2015), while Wards 3, 5, and 6 share another year (most recently 2017).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson is known for being a trailblazer in voluntary partial publicly financed campaigns.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Since 1985, both mayoral and council candidates have been eligible to receive matching public funds from the city.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] To become eligible, council candidates must receive 200 donations of $10 or more (300 for a mayoral candidate).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Candidates must then agree to spending limits equal to 33¢ for every registered Tucson voter, or $79,222 in 2005 (the corresponding figures for mayor are 64¢ per registered voter, or $142,271 in 2003).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In return, candidates receive matching funds from the city at a 1:1 ratio of public money to private donations.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The only other limitation is that candidates may not exceed 75% of the limit by the date of the primary.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Many cities, such as San Francisco and New York City, have copied this system, albeit with more complex spending and matching formulas.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Mayor Regina Romero (D) was sworn into office on December 2, 2019, succeeding Jonathan Rothschild (D) who was sworn into office on December 5, 2011, succeeding Robert E.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Primarily, students of the Tucson area attend public schools in the Tucson Unified School District (TUSD).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] TUSD has the second highest enrollment of any school district in Arizona, behind Mesa Unified School District in the Phoenix metropolitan area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] There are also many publicly funded charter schools with a specialized curriculum.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Other notable districts include Sunnyside Unified School District, Marana Unified School District, Amphitheater Unified School District, Vail Unified School District, and Flowing Wells Unified School District.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In 1956, Tucson High School had the largest enrollment of any secondary school in the United States, with a total of more than 6,800 students.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson has one daily newspaper, the morning *Arizona Daily Star*.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Wick Communications publishes the daily legal paper *The Daily Territorial*, while Boulder, Colo.-based 10/13 Communications publishes *Tucson Weekly* (an "alternative" publication), *Inside Tucson Business* and the *Explorer*.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] TucsonSentinel.com is a nonprofit independent online news organization.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] *Tucson Lifestyle Magazine*, *Lovin' Life in Tucson*, *DesertLeaf*, and *Zócalo Magazine* are monthly publications covering arts, architecture, decor, fashion, entertainment, business, history, and other events.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The *Arizona Daily Wildcat* is the University of Arizona's student newspaper, and the *Aztec News* is the Pima Community College student newspaper.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] *Catholic Outlook* is the newspaper for the Roman Catholic Diocese of Tucson, and the *Arizona Jewish Post* is the newspaper of the Jewish Federation of Southern Arizona.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Defunct newspapers include *Weekly Arizonian*, the state's first newspaper, founded 1859 and defunct 1871, *Tucson Citizen*, defunct 2009, and *El Tucsonense,* a Spanish language paper defunct 1963.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The Tucson metro area is served by many local television stations and is the 65th largest designated market area (DMA) in the U.S. with 433,330 homes (0.39% of the total U.S.).
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson's primary electrical power source is a natural gas power plant managed by Tucson Electric Power that is within the city limits on the southwestern boundary of Davis-Monthan Air-force base adjacent to Interstate 10.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The air pollution generated has raised some concerns as the Sundt operating station has been online since 1962 and is exempt from many pollution standards and controls due to its age.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Solar has been gaining ground in Tucson with its ideal over 300 days of sunshine climate.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Federal, state, and even local utility credits and incentives have also enticed residents to equip homes with solar systems.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Davis-Monthan AFB has a 3.3 Megawatt (MW) ground-mounted solar photovoltaic (PV) array and a 2.7 MW rooftop-mounted PV array, both of which are in the Base Housing area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The base will soon have the largest solar-generating capacity in the United States Department of Defense after awarding a contract on September 10, 2010, to SunEdison to construct a 14.5 MW PV field on the northwestern side of the base.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Global Solar Energy, which is at Tech Parks Arizona, is one of the planet's largest CIGS solar fields at 750 kilowatts.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson and Pima County adopted dark sky ordinances to control light pollution in support of the region's astronomical observatories in 1972.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Less than 100 years ago, the Santa Cruz River flowed nearly year-round through Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] This supply of water has slowly disappeared, causing Tucson to seek alternative sources.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In 1881, water was pumped from a well on the banks of the Santa Cruz River and flowed by gravity through pipes into the distribution system.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson currently draws water from two main sources: Central Arizona Project (CAP) water and groundwater.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In 1992, Tucson Water delivered CAP water to some customers that was unacceptable due to discoloration, bad odor and flavor, as well as problems it caused with some customers' plumbing and appliances.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson's city water currently consists of CAP water mixed with groundwater.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In an effort to conserve water, Tucson is recharging groundwater supplies by running part of its share of CAP water into various open portions of local rivers to seep into their aquifer.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Additional study is scheduled to determine how much water is lost through evaporation from the open areas, especially during the summer.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The City of Tucson provides reclaimed water to its inhabitants, but it is only used for "applications such as irrigation, dust control, and industrial uses".
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] These resources have been in place for more than 27 years, and deliver to over 900 locations.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Since 2001, CAP water has allowed the city to remove or turn off over 80 wells.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The city of Tucson, Arizona provides financial incentives for residents to harvest their rainwater.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson's water supply, like many Western cities, is drawn from two main sources: surface water that is pumped more than 300 miles (480 km) from the Colorado River and groundwater.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The pump expends a significant amount of energy and the Colorado River is diminishing as a result of climate change and overuse.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In 2012, the city began a program that rebates residents as much as $2,000 for the purchase of water harvesting systems.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] "Water harvesting" refers to rainwater, which is gathered from building surfaces, and stormwater*,* which collects nonpotable storm runoff from streets and earth.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The program is financed by a water bill fee of 10 cents per 748 gallons of city water used.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In the first few years, the rebate program was not conserving water as efficiently as they anticipated.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] But in fiscal year 2018–2019, the rebate program saved 52.1 million gallons of water.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] That is enough water to meet the annual usage of 160 households.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The city has been trying to grow the approximately 250 people who obtain active rebates each year by introducing a loan program to bring rebates within reach of lower-income residents.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The city government has an ambitious goal to be carbon neutral by 2030 and is integrating changes that will help change local resident's conventional thinking and practices.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] On May 1, 2020, Tucson began charging residents and businesses within city limits a monthly Green Stormwater Infrastructure fee (13 cents per 748 gallons of city water used), which is projected to raise some $3 million a year for public stormwater capture installations and other projects.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] But this comes at a time when unemployment is rising and the number of low income residents facing unaffordable bills between 2010 and 2018 doubled to 46% as the average bill increased by 119% in Tucson.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Additionally, as part of the citywide climate resiliency effort, Mayor Regina Romero recently announced the planting of a million trees over the next decade.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson's Sun Tran bus system serves greater Tucson with standard, express, regional shuttle, and on-demand shuttle bus service.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] It was awarded Best Transit System in 1988 and 2005.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] A 3.9-mile (6.3 km) streetcar line, Sun Link, connects the University of Arizona campus with 4th Avenue, downtown, and the Mercado District west of Interstate 10 and the Santa Cruz River.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Ten-minute headway passenger service began July 25, 2014.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The streetcar uses Sun Tran's card payment and transfer system, connecting with the University of Arizona's CatTran shuttles, Amtrak, and Greyhound intercity bus service.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Sun Tran has been fare-free since the spring of 2020.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Initially this change was made to limit contact between riders and drivers due to the COVID-19 pandemic, but the city council voted to eliminate fares indefinitely in 2023.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Amtrak, the national passenger rail system, provides service to Tucson three times weekly in both directions, operating its *Sunset Limited* between Los Angeles, California and New Orleans, Louisiana; and *Texas Eagle* service between Los Angeles and Chicago, Illinois.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson International Airport (IATA: **TUS**, ICAO: **KTUS**), is 6 mi (9.7 km) south of the city's center.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] TIA is the second-largest commercial airport in Arizona (behind Sky Harbor in Phoenix), providing nonstop flights to 15 destinations throughout the United States.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] In addition to passenger and freight service, TIA supports the 162nd Fighter Wing's fleet of seventy F-16s stationed at the Tucson Air National Guard Base.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] There are two general aviation reliever airports in the area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] The city of Tucson operates Ryan Airfield 13 miles (21 km) southwest of the city center, and the town of Marana operates Marana Regional Airport 15 miles (24 km) to the northwest.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Pinal Airpark is also within the metropolitan area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] There are two Interstate highways in the metropolitan area.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Interstate 10 runs southeast from Phoenix through Marana, passes west of downtown, and continues east toward El Paso.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Interstate 19 leaves the I-10 south of downtown and heads south to the Mexican border.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Arizona State Route 210 is a shorter expressway that links downtown with Davis-Monthan Air Force Base and Tucson's southeast side.
[src:gluhareff-emg-300/tucson-arizona-p02] Tucson does not have a beltway system, and relies almost entirely on surface streets.
